creating new images and from running instances - hands on

AMI - backup from the os level
snapshot - only backup of volume.

AMI (Amazon Machine Image)

Simple line: AMI is a full backup of the instance at the OS level.
Example: You configure an EC2 with Ubuntu, install Apache, MySQL, and your app. Then you create an AMI. Later, you can launch new EC2 instances from this AMI, and they’ll have the same OS, software, and configuration already set up.

Snapshot

Simple line: Snapshot is a backup of the volume (storage) only.
Example: Your EC2 has an EBS volume storing a database. You take a snapshot of that volume. If something goes wrong, you can restore the volume from the snapshot, but it won’t include the OS or instance configuration — just the data stored in that disk.

